body:
Using graalvm 20.2 based on Java 8 on macOS 10.15 I've managed to successfully build a native image the following way:

```shell
/path/to/graal/java -agentlib:native-image-agent=config-output-dir=META-INF -cp .:onnxruntime-1.4.0.jar sample.ScoreMNIST cnn_mnist_pytorch.onnx mnist.t
/path/to/graal/native-image -H:+JNI -H:+ReportExceptionStackTraces -H:+StackTrace -H:ConfigurationFileDirectories=META-INF --no-server --no-fallback -cp .:onnxruntime-1.4.0.jar sample.ScoreMNIST
```

Had a few false starts which I'm not so sure about (I had to run the java agent a couple of times to get all the JNI codepaths, and there were some other issues), but I ended up with a roughly 35 MB binary which can score both the cnn and logistic regression test models in the java folder.

Unfortunately I don't know anything about Quarkus and it's build process, so after you've checked you're on the latest Graal it might be worth talking to them about how to get the command line parameters for native image in the right place.

This is the jni-config.json file generated from the agent:
```json

[
{
  "name":"ai.onnxruntime.MapInfo",
  "methods":[{"name":"<init>","parameterTypes":["int","ai.onnxruntime.OnnxJavaType","ai.onnxruntime.OnnxJavaType"] }]
},
{
  "name":"ai.onnxruntime.NodeInfo",
  "methods":[{"name":"<init>","parameterTypes":["java.lang.String","ai.onnxruntime.ValueInfo"] }]
},
{
  "name":"ai.onnxruntime.NodeInfo[]"
},
{
  "name":"ai.onnxruntime.OnnxJavaType",
  "methods":[{"name":"mapFromOnnxTensorType","parameterTypes":["ai.onnxruntime.TensorInfo$OnnxTensorType"] }]
},
{
  "name":"ai.onnxruntime.OnnxSequence",
  "methods":[{"name":"<init>","parameterTypes":["long","long","ai.onnxruntime.SequenceInfo"] }]
},
{
  "name":"ai.onnxruntime.OnnxTensor",
  "methods":[{"name":"<init>","parameterTypes":["long","long","ai.onnxruntime.TensorInfo"] }]
},
{
  "name":"ai.onnxruntime.OnnxValue"
},
{
  "name":"ai.onnxruntime.OnnxValue[]"
},
{
  "name":"ai.onnxruntime.SequenceInfo",
  "methods":[{"name":"<init>","parameterTypes":["int","ai.onnxruntime.MapInfo"] }]
},
{
  "name":"ai.onnxruntime.TensorInfo",
  "methods":[{"name":"<init>","parameterTypes":["long[]","ai.onnxruntime.OnnxJavaType","ai.onnxruntime.TensorInfo$OnnxTensorType"] }]
},
{
  "name":"ai.onnxruntime.TensorInfo$OnnxTensorType",
  "methods":[{"name":"mapFromInt","parameterTypes":["int"] }]
},
{
  "name":"java.lang.ClassLoader",
  "methods":[{"name":"loadClass","parameterTypes":["java.lang.String"] }]
},
{
  "name":"java.lang.ClassNotFoundException"
},
{
  "name":"java.lang.String"
},
{
  "name":"java.lang.String[]"
}
]
```
The reflect config didn't have anything onnx related in it, and the resource-config.json was this:
```json
{
  "resources":[
    {"pattern":"\\QMETA-INF/services/jdk.vm.ci.hotspot.HotSpotJVMCIBackendFactory\\E"}, 
    {"pattern":"\\QMETA-INF/services/jdk.vm.ci.services.JVMCIServiceLocator\\E"}, 
    {"pattern":"\\Qai/onnxruntime/native/osx-x64/libonnxruntime.dylib\\E"}, 
    {"pattern":"\\Qai/onnxruntime/native/osx-x64/libonnxruntime4j_jni.dylib\\E"}
  ],
  "bundles":[]
}
``` 

Note if you're using other native codepaths (e.g. the `java.nio.Buffer` tensor creation, or the metadata loader, etc) you'll need to make sure those are exercised in the java run with the agent turned on.
